{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b09be5e3-6c05-45ab-8467-027bffb35eb6","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 enables **implicit span conversions** by default. `int[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, so overload resolution prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)   // ← now wins\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nBecause `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be captured in an expression tree — hence the runtime failure.\n\n## Fix\n\nForce the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nOr call it explicitly as a static method:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither approach bypasses the span overload and restores the original behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fccf6281-0f55-44f1-a76a-4cf1414c8f9d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves extension methods. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension members** (a new feature), but more relevantly, there's a change in how `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` is resolved for arrays.\n\nThe key issue: In earlier versions of C#, when you wrote `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]`, the compiler would resolve this to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` — a static method call. Expression trees can represent static method calls fine.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, arrays now implement `ICollection<T>` directly, so the compiler prefers the instance method `ICollection<T>.Contains` over the extension method. This is the breaking change — expression trees have trouble representing instance method calls on arrays in certain contexts, or the method resolution itself changed in a way that breaks existing code.\n\nActually, I think the real culprit is that `.Contains()` on an array now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `Span<T>`, which uses `ref` parameters that can't be represented in expression trees. With the implicit `T[]` to `Span<T>` conversion available in C# 13+, the compiler picks this overload instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, causing the expression tree compilation to fail. The real problem is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` expects a `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which is a `ref struct` type that expression trees can't represent, so the compiler fails when trying to build the expression tree with this newer overload resolution. I can fix this by explicitly casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older `Enumerable.Contains` method instead, or by using...\n\nWriting code examples... I'm trying to figure out whether this is actually a compile-time error that the compiler should catch, or if something about the .NET 10 upgrade is allowing it to slip through to runtime. The user mentioned `preferInterpretation: true`, which suggests the expression tree might be getting interpreted rather than compiled, but I'm still uncertain about the exact mechanism causing the runtime failure instead of a compile-time error. code previously compiled and worked. In .NET 10, if the compiler resolves to the span overload, it should give a compile-time error for expression trees, not a runtime error.\n\nUnless the expression tree is constructed via reflection at runtime, or method resolution happens differently. Maybe it IS a compile-time error and the user is just describing it loosely as a runtime failure. Or there's a different mechanism at play.\n\nLooking more carefully, there was a specific change in overload resolution with the new extension types in C# 14. The code might compile because the compiler doesn't catch the issue in all expression tree cases, but then fails at runtime when the expression tree interpreter tries to evaluate it against a ref struct.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that implicit span conversions were added in C# 13 with .NET 9. Arrays can now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so when overload resolution picks between the span version and the `IEnumerable` version, the span overload wins because it's the better conversion. This was a documented breaking change for .NET 9, and the user might be hitting it when upgrading from an earlier version.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly cast to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the compiler to use the `Enumerable.Contains` overload instead of the span version, which can't be used in expression trees.","outputTokens":2464,"requestId":"D819:271EF2:605CAC4:692ADAB:69F15662"},"id":"02042564-809a-49b0-920c-3ad6ef3cda55","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:53:41.300Z","parentId":"85a2f6da-8af5-4aec-a1d9-a85d8cf41669"}
